oracle.mapviewer.share
Class Field

java.lang.Object
  oracle.mapviewer.share.Field
All Implemented Interfaces:
java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Cloneable, java.lang.Comparable
public class Field
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Cloneable, java.lang.Comparable

A Field object typically represents a value of a particular type or table column.
Sometimes it is also used to represent just the type information of a column (such as its SQL type name, name of the column or alias), without an actual value.
Note that the Java type information is always set when representing a concrete value (during the construction of this object), while the SQL type information is set by application only.

createField

public static Field createField(java.lang.String value,
                                java.lang.String type)
Creates a properly typed Field object from the given string representation of a value and the type of the value.
The following basic type names are supported (case insensitive):
  • string
  • int
  • integer
  • float
  • double
  • long
  • char
  • short
  • byte
  • date
  • time
  • timestamp

if type is null, then a String type is assumed.

Parameters:
value - - string representation of a value
type - - type of the value (such as "integer", "string", "date")

setNameAndKey

public void setNameAndKey(java.lang.String name,
                          boolean isKey,
                          java.lang.String displayName)
Sets the optional name, isKey flag and displayName for this attribute. There are no relationship between these 3 parameters, and any or all of them can be null/false. This method is simply provided as a conveience (instead of writing 3 separate methods setName, setKey and setDisplayName).
By default, Field is constructed with both name and displayName being null, and isKey being false.

Parameters:
name - - field name
isKey - - primary key flag
displayName - - alias name to be used in applications

equals

public boolean equals(java.lang.Object o)
Returns if Field objects are equal. A deep comparison of all aspects of the two Fields. If only interested in the equal-ness of the value aspect, use the method comapreTo.

Overrides:
equals in class java.lang.Object
Parameters:
o - - the Field object to be comapred.
Returns:
boolean - true if every aspect of the two Fields match, including the display names, the type information, and of course the values. false otherwise.

compareTo

public int compareTo(java.lang.Object o)
Compares two Field objects using their value's natural order. All other aspects of the Field objects (such as display names) are ignored for the comparison.
Note that filed1.compareTo(field2)==0 does NOT necessiarily mean field1.equals(field2)==true, as the latter requires exhaustive comparison on all aspects of the two Field objects.

Specified by:
compareTo in interface java.lang.Comparable
Parameters:
o - - the Field object to be compared.
Returns:
int - the value 0 if this Field is equal to the argument Field; a value less than 0 if this Field is less than the argument Field; and a value greater than 0 if this Field is greater than the argument Field.
Throws:
java.lang.ClassCastException - - if the argument is not a Field, or if the values are not comparable.

setContexts

public void setContexts(java.lang.String[] param)
A Field can have one ore more optional contexts. Each context is basically a name-value pair. All the contexts are stored in a single String type array such as ["name1", "value1", "name2", "value2", ... ].

Parameters:
param - - context parameters

getContexts

public java.lang.String[] getContexts()
Returns currently set contexts, or null if none is set. Contexts are custom name-value pairs that can be interepreted by an application.

Returns:
String[] - a String array containing name/value pairs; or null if no context has been set.
